## ROOT CAUSE

**File: polymorph.c, lines 191-198**

The `convert_fileName()` function contains a classic stack buffer overflow vulnerability. The function declares a fixed-size stack buffer `newname[MAX]` where MAX is 2048 bytes (defined in polymorph_types.h:9). 

At line 191, there is a for-loop that iterates through every character of the input string `original`:
```c
for(i=0;i<strlen(original);i++)
```

Inside this loop, characters are written to `newname[i]` at lines 193 and 196 without any bounds checking to ensure `i < MAX`. When the input filename exceeds 2048 characters (as in the test case with ~3000+ 'A' characters), the loop continues writing past the end of the `newname` buffer, overwriting adjacent stack memory including saved frame pointers and the return address.

The loop iterates `strlen(original)` times, and when `strlen(original) > 2048`, indices from 2048 onwards write beyond the allocated buffer. Line 198 then writes a null terminator at `newname[i]` (where i == strlen(original)), further corrupting the stack.

Additionally, line 200 in the else branch uses `strcpy(newname, original)` which also lacks bounds checking and will overflow when original exceeds MAX bytes.

